markdown: The WU Speakers Bureau and How It Operates When Russia launched Sputnik I, the WU Speakers Bureau received re- quests for faculty members to discuss travel to the moon. This topic isn't mentioned in the bureau's brochure, but hopeful calls came in anyway. Although no Jules Vernes were available, compromises were worked out. The brochure, a blue - and - white folder listing topics offered, was sent last fall to program chairmen of women's clubs, church groups, P-TAs and other service groups in the St. Louis area. Regularly revised, the new booklet lists topics suggested by faculty mem- bers. No names are given. "This way," points out Miss Eileen Wolff, director of the bu- reau, "the faculty members aren't bothered by calls from organizations. It saves time and <::A black and white photograph of Miss Wolff, a woman with short, styled hair and a necklace, looking directly at the camera. : figure::> MISS WOLFF trouble for both pro- fessor and organization if arrange- ments can be made through the bu- reau." Some faculty members, long known in the community as good speakers, are still approached directly by many groups. But the campus office strives <::A black and white photograph shows three people, two women and one man, seated at a table. The woman on the left has light hair and is wearing a dark, possibly plaid, shirt. The woman in the middle has dark hair styled back, is wearing a light-colored patterned blouse and a necklace, and is looking down at something on the table, possibly signing a document. The man on the right has dark hair, is wearing a suit jacket and a tie, and is also looking down at the table, smiling. All three appear to be engaged in an activity at the table.: figure::> Conferring on talks by the Panel of Americans are MISS KENDRA ELLIS (left), a freshman; MRS. MARTIN TADO, faculty co-ordinator, and DR. EARNEST BRANDENBURG, dean of University College and associate professor of speech. University College sponsors the student group. steadily to inform these organizations that it will serve as "middleman" and take care of time-consuming details. The Speakers Bureau, part of the program of the Office of Information since 1956, grew out of an informal tradition of the University. Names of available speakers had been kept in a file inherited in 1953 by University College. Callers were given names of professors willing to speak on desired subjects. University College completed arrangements for the talks. Organization of the Speakers Bureau on its present basis is a product of the University's Second Century Development Program. In its first year of operation, the bureau drew on a wide variety of speakers. Talks given covered such diverse matters as col- lege football, D. H. Lawrence's poetry, community ideals, China and the Far East, children's behavior problems and WU excavations in Greece. A Panel of Americans, the only student speakers scheduled by the bureau, appeared before several organizations last fall. Active on campus since 1948, this panel is part of a national project designed to promote inter-faith and interracial understanding. Organizations needing speakers must make the overtures. For its part, the bureau stands ready to expand its work in an effort to strengthen ties between community and University. N.M.B. WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY ST. LOUIS 5, MISSOURI <::A black and white photograph shows Miss Jaquelin Ambler, an alumna and Fulbright scholar in art history, examining a model of a new Music Department unit. She is seated at a table, looking down and to her right at the model.::> MISS JAQUELIN AMBLER, alum- na and Fulbright scholar in art history, examines model of new Music Department unit. Other planned additions will also help WU fulfill its growing role as a cultural center for parents and for other adults in the community. <::attestation: Postage Mark Status: PAID Readable Text: Non-Profit Organization United States Postage St. Louis (Mo.) Permit No. 1721 Description: Rectangular postage mark with text indicating paid status and permit number.::> Source: https://www.industrydocuments.ucsf.edu/docs/yrpf0227
